segments.text: Okay.
Have you had a chance to interview John Bertrand?
No.
If we could ever get him here.
He is now president of, what is it?
I can never remember the name.
The Barry.
The Barry School.
President of the Barry School.
He could tell you a great deal because he was
in the formative period of the basic division.
When I was with them, of course, it was just the freshman annex.
But he was there when the division itself was organized as a union.
for administering the work of all freshmen.
When you say he was there in the formative, this would be at the time it was established at the end?
Yes, and then he became its dean.
And he stayed with it then until it was disbanded as a separate unit?
Yes.
Here again, my memory may be tricking me a little bit.
I'm not sure that he did not become president of the Berry schools before the Basic Division was disbanded.
But I'm sure you've got a record of that, and you can check on that.
I think I have some material on the Basic Division.
And I can tell you someone else who knows a great deal about it is Cliff Randstuhl, who is associate dean of the
College of Engineering.
He and I and John were all associated with the freshman annex in the basic division.
Well, I think it's commonly stated around here that one reason for it was to help control the hazing.
You know, this is why the freshmen were chosen to go off campus rather than, say, the seniors.
But I presume the freshman class was the largest, so it also would be the best one to have separated that you had to separate.
Exactly.
You then... Oh, I do know.
John Bertrand did leave before the basic division was disbanded, and he was followed by Dr.
Kahn, who later became president of Oklahoma State University.
I think he left us to become dean of the College of Arts and Sciences there and then was later made president.
Oklahoma State.
So you went from the head of the basic division and also you were, I guess, as assistant dean of the college, your responsibility was being head of the basic division.
Is that?
That's it, yeah.
And then you became the dean of arts and sciences for about three years.
From, yes.
For four years.
Longer than that, yes.
It was four years, I guess it was.
And then dean of the college for another...
Three or four years.
Then went on leave with the Commission on Higher Education as its first program examiner.
I was with them for 15 months and then came back to the Department of English and remained in it until I retired in 72.
Were there any significant occurrences while, say, you were dean of arts and sciences, any significant changes that were made in that particular area that might bear mentioning?
Did you start any new programs or anything of that nature?
Yes, although I doubt if I could claim much credit for them.

What had been a department in the College of, I mean in the School of Agriculture, called Agricultural Administration, became a department in the College of Liberal Arts, the Department of Business, under Professor Leland, Professor Tom Leland.
And it was also at that time that the Department of Oceanography was created and assigned to the College of Arts and Sciences under its first head, Dale Leper, Dr. Leper.
Now, it was the Department of Oceanography then, although one of its options was meteorology and became, of course, later on, a program on its own.
And those two things were done.
I don't believe any other departments were established then.
No, education and psychology was still there.
Of course, the makeup, and I'm sure old catalogs would show you this,
was entirely different from what it is as a College of Liberal Arts.
As a matter of fact, I have been spun off from the College of Liberal Arts, the College of Science, the College of Geosciences, the College of Business Administration.
And education.
And the College of Education.
They've all spun off.
Arts and Sciences.
From Arts and Sciences.
So you, in a sense, while you were dean of arts and sciences, you had everything that wasn't even, that wasn't either engineering or agriculture.
I'll better name that.
Yes.
Okay.
Then you went up to the, I say went up, I presume it was a promotion up to the dean of the college, which was equivalent to current vice president for academic affairs, which then puts you what?

uh one level below the president at that time of course we also had a chancellor so the the president was one level below the chancellor and i was below the president kind of executive deanship so the the the deans of this other schools of the various schools reported through you to the press to the president of texas that's right
I noted that you asked to be relieved of that position and go back to full-time teaching.
Was that, had you had about all that you wanted of administration?
Just about.
And you enjoyed the teaching more than you did administration, I take it?
I also enjoyed my work with the commission.
15 months I was with them.
Let's see, when you went back to teaching of English, I take it you had not been doing any teaching while you were in these various administrative positions.
I continued to teach as long as I was at the annex, but after that I did not teach any more.
By the time you went back to the department, you were then offering graduate degrees, I believe, were you not?
Or did masters come in later than that?
I think masters didn't come in right away.
Let's see.
Although it was not long before we began to offer a master's degree.
And then, of course, still later the doctorate.
And I am really very happy, in a small way, that I was able to stay with the department
long enough to see two doctoral candidates through.
You chaired the committee for two doctoral candidates.
That's right.
And I'm sure served on other committees as well.
Oh, yeah.
Back to this service on the Texas Commission on Higher Education, you were their first program examiner.
Would you explain just exactly what that means?
The staff at that time consisted of three people and some clerical help.
There was the director, who was Dr. Ralph Green, now with the Federal Reserve Bank in Dallas.
There was the program examiner, and I will fill that position, and there was a finance examiner,
who was Dr. Walker from the University of Texas.
And that was the staff.
Of course, I should say this.
We were staff people working for the members of the commission.
And we had to define our own job.
We had to plan it.
We had to get the whole organization going.
Because it was brand new at that point.
It was brand new, yes.
And we had to find out really what we were to do.

Now, as program examiner, it was my job to become familiar with all the academic offerings and all of the publicly supported institutions of higher education, not including junior colleges, which were

at that time under the Texas Education Agency but all the four-year institutions familiarize myself with them and make recommendations to the commission on whether some programs should be deleted or whether programs should be added
And we also made recommendations, as the present commission does, on petitions for new programs.
We made recommendations to members of the commission.
There was a great deal of talk at that time throughout the state about proliferation and institutions were proliferating programs and costing the state an unholy amount of money.
And the commission was created, among other things, to see if there was this proliferation.
Of course, the tremendous growth in students later on made that purely academic, an academic question, but it was not an academic question at the time at all.
And another thing, of course, was to see if it was possible to make sense out of appropriation.

instead of having every president go to the legislature and get what he could on whatever basis he could, this was an effort to do it logically and according to some kind of formula so that everybody would be treated the same way as everybody else.
And formulas are still in existence.
We've tried recently to change that for him.
Yeah.
Not to go off the formula system, but I think we tried for the library in view of the fact that we have to serve as Ag's extension and experiment station.
We tried to get a different formula for library support for A&M.
In fact, we may well have outgrown that conception of the formula.
But it made an awful lot of sense then.
I was lucky enough to sit in on many of the meetings, even of the
from the financial side because the program was involved so much in the financing.

Say if a college or university in Texas at that point wanted to start an entirely new program, say they wanted to begin offering a degree in business administration where they had not in the past, did that proposal to create that new program come through your office then?
Yes.
But by the same token, if you saw the need for a new department somewhere, you could recommend that, I take it.
Although, to my knowledge, that was never done.
Were there many programs?
It could have been.
At first, the commission was, as you might expect, very, very conservative.
And it...
It scrutinized very carefully every request, even for new courses, not new programs, not new degree programs, but even new courses.
The commission, I thought, when I was with them, was a very fine body and a dedicated group of people.

i think they did look upon themselves as representing not parts of the state but the state as a whole i don't know whether that remained true of later commissions or not but it was true i think of that first one has has the work the type of work that you did for the commission has that been taken over now by the coordinating board that's yeah the coordinating board succeeded the commission on higher education okay uh
Well, I know what I'm going to ask.
Were there many programs that were proposed but subsequently turned down while you were in the commissioner's office?
No, because there were not very many that were proposed in the 15 months that I was there.
I think that the institutions probably were deliberately holding back a little bit to see how the commission would function and let it get on its feet.
I think some requests were made almost immediately after I came back.
Did you know when you went to the commission as program examiner that you would be there only one year?
I had gone on leave only for a year.
I suspect I could have gotten an extension.
I think I would have been granted an extension.
And I almost asked for it, but then I did want to get back to my teaching.
It must have been quite an honor for you to be the one person selected from the whole state of Texas to occupy that position.
Well, I don't know how much of an honor it was, but it was certainly a very enjoyable experience and a very worthwhile one.
But I mean, they had to be somebody with some degree of knowledge about college administration in that position.
Well, I certainly appreciated the fact that Dr. Green, who was the director, did ask me to come and serve his program exam.
Well, as I said, you were the one person from the whole state.
Well, he could have found others, I'm sure.
But he did come to you and asked you.
Yes, he did.
So then in 57, and you returned in the fall of 57, I think, you returned back to College Station and resumed your teaching.
Did you still have to do mostly freshman English at that point?
No.
No, I did not at that time.
Although, and this may sound surprising, I wanted to teach freshmen and almost always had at least one section of freshmen.
I had a belief then, and I'm not sure that I've changed it since, that senior members of the department ought to teach freshmen.
So I really asked for at least one freshman section.
Now that was not true later on as we got much, much bigger.
I gradually dropped my freshman word, but that was not for a number of years after I came back, well into the 60s when we were having graduate courses and so on.
I'm not so sure that I still don't think that senior members of a department should teach freshmen.
Well, I think that's a fairly widely held opinion in certain areas.
I know that when I was at Ohio State, every faculty member in the history department had one section of freshman history each year.
So no matter how long you'd been at Ohio State, you still taught freshman history one semester.
And I say that
realizing that sometimes a graduate assistant is a better teacher of freshmen than maybe a senior member.
But I think it's for the good of the senior member as much as for the good of freshmen.
Well, I think at times, however, a graduate assistant, maybe not quite so much, but a brand new PhD, I think, has a tendency to expect far too much from
Freshmen, perhaps many of them, have not had a very good background in high school.
That could be.
We had some inkling of that last year here when a young fellow had done a lot of work up here for a paper he had to write.
I think he came back and told us that, I don't know, something like 70% or 80% of the class had not passed the course.
And this was a new faculty member who, unfortunately, was not going to be back the following year.
The student, at least, his version of it was that the faculty member showed a great lack of concern for the students under him.
But I think that this young PhD had expected a great deal more than he should have from freshman.
I think I found myself in the same trap when I taught high school history for one year.
I expected more of my students than I should have.
And I've observed that when my son has had
new graduates as teachers in the public schools that they sometimes expect far more than they should.
And someone who's had some more experience knows more of what to expect from a course.
Plus, I think in some respects, it's better for the freshman student to have someone who's had a fair amount of experience in teaching.
Yes.
And it is quite possible that the fledgling instructor
expects more than he should.

Well, his most recent experience has been with his own graduate studies, and if he had to read 150 pages a week and write three term papers in the semester, why, then he figured freshmen ought to be able to do that too.
Yeah.
And I would think a graduate student at least ought to be somewhat more mature and be able to budget his time better than many freshmen are able to do.
So you continued to teach in the English department until you retired then in 72.
Was most of that recent service under one department head or was that under more than one?
It was under more than one.
Dr. Stuart Morgan for most of that time
He had replaced Dr. Mayo, who also had asked to be relieved of administrative work.
And Dr. Morgan then was had for many years until his own retirement to modified service.
He was followed by Dr. John Anderson, who subsequently went to the University of Houston.
He was followed by Dr. Lee Martin, who died while here, and he was followed by Dr. Hurth, the present here.
And I was under Dr. Hurth, Dr. Martin, and on through to Morgan.
Okay.
A year ago you were chosen as the speaker for A&M's first formal summer commencement, and I believe I wrote you at that time and you didn't have a copy of your speech.
No, I didn't.
I'm not going to ask you for a copy now.
But anyway, did you look upon that as somewhat of an honor to have been chosen as the first

summer commencement speaker indeed yes i would have considered it an honor to be asked to speak to graduating students yes there is one honor that i have been proud of i mean as a teacher i was fortunate enough to be the recipient of one of the faculty achievement awards oh back in 1962
Six years after I came back into teaching.
Well, I think anybody would be justifiably proud to receive one of those achievement awards and the fact that they give out 12 in a year and what they're now about.
something over 1,000 members of the faculty, I believe.
I think you're right.
So maybe like one in 1,000 gets one now.
That's a fairly small percentage.
Yeah, that's a small percentage.
I've been somewhat interested in the last couple of years from which I've attended that many of them are relatively new faculty members, particularly who received the teaching awards.
Some of the research awards go on occasion to older faculty members.
I think that's really very encouraging that the younger teachers are very

Well, I think some of our newer members, this will sound kind of odd after what I just got through saying about the young man in English faculty, but I think some of our newer teachers have come along at a point where technology has advanced so much that they are more familiar with some of the teaching aids than some of the older ones.
Oh, unquestionably, that enters into it.
Therefore, they can make a more interesting learning experience for their students
someone who has not had the experience and does not have the capabilities of working with the teaching aides that are available.
Have you noticed in the many years you've been here any degree of changes in the types or quality of students which we have
had.
I am told that statistics indicate very clearly that on the average the preparation of our students has been better than it was in earlier year.
But of course
When I came, it was possible to know a major part of all the students.
I mean, for a faculty member to know them.
And I think when you get to know students individually, you tend to rate them very highly because they are not statistics to you.
And so while I'm quite sure the statistics are accurate, that on the average, our entering students do have better preparation than they once had.
I think it would be awfully hard to beat some of those earlier students who of course went on and did make names for themselves in all kinds of occupations.

I wonder whether maybe some of that is that perhaps a larger percentage of our students are now coming from larger cities where the public high school education is perhaps a little bit more advanced than it is in some of the rural areas
from which we got most of our students a few decades ago.
Of course, we also have a better retention rate now, do we not, than we did?
I haven't really seen any statistics.
I've had people tell me that they think that we retain more than we used to.
And how much of that is because of academic, and I've had some indication that some of the people left because of the military aspect.
Well, that was true.
And with the lessening of that, I would think, that factor would decline in importance.
But...
I guess there's no question, what if the students are better prepared when they come?
They're better able to cope with the increased difficulty of the learning process.
And you were asking me at the beginning of our talk, what could you do in the bachelor club?
Well, there's more for students to do now, huh?
Undoubtedly, there is.
There used to be a general exodus
Friday afternoon.
Students would go as far away as Dallas or Fort Worth or San Antonio.
And while there may still be an exodus, I don't know.
I suspect that there is so much more for students to do here that there's not the felt need to go.
We had one
commandant, a very salty commandant, who made a remark I'll never forget.
He said, if we had a one-way court trip to hell, there would be some students who wanted to leave a day early.
And that was pretty true.
You know, for a long time we had a six-day week.
His classes were held Saturday.
It was not until I was in administrative work that we reserved Saturday for the military part of the program and went to a five-day college week.
I believe, let's see, in, what, 62, when there was the previous self-study, you were in charge of that.
Only as the editor.
Editor of the final report.
Yes.
But I believe someone told me that your review at that point, at least the published review, was not quite as elaborate as the one... No.
Nothing like.
In fact, I was amazed at how much more complex this...
years' self-study, or rather, I mean, this time's self-study was than the one that we did.
That was our first experience, and I think everybody in the institution was groping his way at that time, and we weren't quite sure, but it was nothing like the elaborate document.
You say that was the first time.
Was A&M not accredited by the Southern Association?
I don't think they had ever...
No, I could be wrong.
I could have been conscious of it before.
But that's the first one I can remember.
A full-scale one.
Well, it seems strange.
You've been a member of the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools for a long, long time.
And maybe they had earlier ones that I just didn't know about, but I don't think so.
I think that was the first one.
Well, certainly you were in an administrative position in the Dean of Arts and Sciences at the time.
The logical previous one would have been.
Well, it would have been.
You would have been involved.
No, this is a much more elaborate.
I know.
I've got 16 feet of a table.
